Text: This week has been fast paced from meeting our client to outlining project specifications and handing in our first report.
I had anticipated this past week to go a little differently although when meeting the client it is clear that there were multiple challenges they wanted our team to tackle.
With the help form Teacher1 and Teacher2, we were able to narrow these specifications down to a more achievable project within the 5 weeks we have available.
I am fortunate to be in a team where we all value peer to peer learning and are eager to help each other out.
I believe this will be a strength of our team as we are all approaching this steep learning curve.

Roro has taken a great lead in uncovering our technical challenges and making the first prototype and getting feedback from our client where Toto was forward thinking in creating slides for the presentation on friday and myself doing the report write up with the notes that were created.
Going forward, it will be nice to communicate more fluently with our client through the Ob3 platform.

He seems eager to help us out with sourcing the information we need to go forward although I am anxious we won't get the feedback and information we need to make decisions in a timely manner, and with only a few short weeks to get the project done, being agile is important.

As our project is extracting data and creating a visual dashboard for platform users as well as for the Ob3 founders, we need to understand the customers pain points and validate this by talking to members of the teaching and learning ecosystem who use Ob3.
Our team has decided to coordinate a focus group to achieve this with the hopes the project founders will be eager to receive this information also.
If the assumed problem for Ob3 users is not validated sufficiently, we will likely create a dashboard that is not of value to our clients.
For this upcoming week our team is aiming to extract more information about the problem from Ob3 users and tailor a solution to fit both our clients needs and the needs of Ob3 users.
We will accomplish this by Toto and myself following the lessons we have learnt through INFO201 about requirements elicitation.
From this we will be able to build UML diagrams, such as ERDâ€™s and Activity Diagrams.
During this week we are all going to learn about Apache Cassandra databases in preparation for undergoing technical developments which will get us ahead of the steep learning curve.
